Uzbek government restricts movement of private transport and as of Mar. 30 issues permits (stickers) to vehicles engaged in the following activities:
"- official vehicles of organizations engaged in the sale of food, drugs and medical devices, as well as personal vehicles of employees in these organizations;
- vehicles of legal entities and individuals engaged in pharmacy activities, manufacturing and retailing sanitary products (means of protection against coronavirus infection and disinfection);
- vehicles owned by legal entities and individual entrepreneurs involved in the construction of hospitals and avenues built in Tashkent region and city of Tashkent.
Personal transport can be used in emergency cases, such as pregnancy and childbirth, in cases of bodily harm, other circumstances that pose a threat to human life."
These restrictions are only applied when driving from one region to another, as well as cities of Tashkent, Nukus (Republic of Karakalpakstan) and district centres. No sticker is required when driving in other cities and regions.

From September 1,2020 restrictions on the entry and exit of cars through checkpoints between Uzbekistan and Kyrgyzstan are lifted in strict accordance with sanitary and hygienic requirements, and the following procedure will be introduced:
- Individuals who have stayed in Kyrgyzstan during last 14 days or have a negative PCR test within the last 72 hours, do not have to undergo quarantine when entering Uzbekistan;
-  citizens of Uzbekistan arriving from Kyrgyzstan, who have been only in Kyrgyzstan, do not have to undergo quarantine when entering Uzbekistan;
- in other cases, arrivals will need to undergo quarantine.

In Uzbekistan, from March 24, 2020, all non-food markets are closed temporarily in Tashkent Region in accordance with the decision of the administration of the Tashkent region. UPDATE: In Uzbekistan, according to the order of the Special Republican Commission on Prevention of the Covid-19 made on April 25, 2020, following business are allowed to resume their operation:
-Markets for building materials, including business entities involved in retail and wholesale trade in building materials (provided that their area is at least 500 sq.);
- Chain stores of large manufacturers, designed to sell their own products (in compliance with the sanitary standard of 10 square meters per 1 buyer);
- Craftsmen - sale in the places (stores) of products created by them, separate from markets;
- Business entities (of any form of ownership) engaged in the cultivation and sale of seeds and seedlings;
- Entrepreneurs (regardless of ownership) engaged in the sale of automotive parts.

In Uzbekistan, from September 5, catering facilities (restaurants, cafes, canteens, teahouses)  will be able to receive guests inside the establishments with the following conditions:
-banquets and other public events are not allowed;
-the distance between tables should be at least 2 m;
-no more than four people should be seated at the table (excluding family members);
-staff must wear medical masks and gloves;
-after each visitor, the surface of the table and other items and accessories should be cleaned with disinfectants;
-disinfecting equipment (ultraviolet lamps, etc.) should be installed, as well as in the air ventilation system.
In addition, theaters and cinemas will reopen with following conditions:
-installation of disinfecting equipment (ultraviolet lamps, etc.), as well as in the air ventilation system.
-visitors should keep social distance and wear a medical mask (if necessary, it is necessary to provide a free replacement of the mask if the event lasts more than 2 hours);
-visitors with a body temperature of 37 degrees and above or with symptoms of the disease should not be allowed;
-clean the seat and other equipment with a disinfectant after each session;
-staff must wear medical masks and gloves.
With similar conditions, attraction parks can also resume their activity.

